---

<Layout
  title="How much does a solar installation cost in Morocco in 2026? | Blog Taqinor"
  description="Indicative 2026 brackets by power, roof, battery and VAT surcharges — to know what to expect before your quote."
  ogSlug="accueil"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(blogPosting)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbLd)} />
  <div class="v2">
    <V2Enhance />
    <Article33Ribbon />

    <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: 'Home', href: L('/') }, { label: 'Blog', href: L('/blog') }, { label: 'How much does a solar installation cost in 2026?' }]} />

    <article class="mx-auto max-w-[68ch] px-4 pb-24 pt-12 sm:pb-28">
      <p class="tech-label v2-kicker rule-brass text-brass-300">
        Blog · {dateFmt.format(pubDate)} · by Reda Kasri
      </p>
      <h1 class="display v2-page-title mt-5 text-white">How much does a solar installation cost in Morocco in 2026?</h1>

      <p class="article-meta mt-3 flex items-center gap-2 text-xs text-lune-faint">
        {readingMinutes} min read
      </p>

      <p class="prose-lead mt-5">Indicative 2026 brackets by power, roof, battery and VAT surcharges — to know what to expect before your quote.</p>

      <div class="prose mt-10">
        <p>
          "How much does it really cost?" is the first sentence of almost every one of my meetings.
          And the reason the figures you find online range from single to triple is easy to explain:
          the price of a panel sitting on a shelf has nothing to do with that of a turnkey
          installation, mounted on your roof and connected. So I'd rather lay out the 2026 Moroccan
          market brackets as they are, with their sources and, above all, their limits.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-lune-faint">
          <em>(W293 — for the evergreen version of these brackets, reviewed every year independently
          of the 2026 news, see our page <a href={L('/prix-panneaux-solaires-maroc')}>Solar panel
          prices in Morocco</a>.)</em>
        </p>

        <h2>Turnkey brackets by power (indicative 2026)</h2>
        <p>
          These prices cover both equipment supply <strong>and</strong> the full installation
          (inverter, wiring, structure, commissioning). They're drawn from Moroccan installer
          publications and online price guides — <strong>indicative 2026 brackets</strong>, not
          official rates.
        </p>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Installed power</th>
                <th>Indicative 2026 bracket (MAD incl. VAT)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {fourchettes.map((f) => (
                <tr>
                  <td>{f.kwc}</td>
                  <td>{f.prix}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          <strong>Average turnkey cost: about 10,000 – 14,000 DH/kWc</strong> (equipment + labour,
          indicative 2026 bracket — sources: solaropeak.com, ecovolt.ma, electrosolarplus.ma,
          lechantier.ma).
        </p>
        <p>
          The spread is real: it reflects roof type, distance to electrical panels, inverter brand,
          and installer margins. An on-site quote remains essential.
        </p>

        <h2>Beware of "4,700 DH/kWc" prices: that's not turnkey</h2>
        <p>
          You'll often see a price around <strong>4,700 DH/kWc</strong> or even lower circulating.
          That figure corresponds to the <strong>equipment kit cost alone</strong> (panels + inverter,
          excluding installation, wiring, structure, connection) — <strong>implausibly low for a
          finished turnkey installation</strong>. Don't compare this figure to the brackets above:
          they're two different realities (indicative 2026 bracket — sources: solaropeak.com,
          ecovolt.ma).
        </p>

        <h2>What makes up the price: equipment and installation</h2>
        <h3>Photovoltaic panels</h3>
        <p>
          Indicative 2026 market price: <strong>~1.0 – 1.5 DH/Wc</strong> for panels alone
          (excluding installation). 550–600 W modules represent the current standard — count on
          about 2 panels per kWc installed.
        </p>
        <h3>The inverter</h3>
        <p>
          Indicative example: a Huawei SUN2000-5K inverter traded around
          <strong> ~12,500 DH</strong> with a 10-year warranty (indicative 2026 market price —
          source: electrosolarplus.ma). The range varies by power and brand.
        </p>
        <h3>Labour and accessories</h3>
        <p>
          Mounting structure, DC/AC wiring, protection panel, administrative steps (Law 82-21
          declaration for installations under 11 kWc) — these items represent a significant share of
          the total turnkey cost.
        </p>

        <h2>Surcharges depending on roof configuration</h2>
        <p>Not all roofs are alike. Some configurations add significant costs:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Tile or corrugated-sheet roof</strong> (more technical installation):
          <strong> +6,000 – 12,000 DH</strong> (indicative 2026 bracket — source:
          electrosolarplus.ma, lechantier.ma)</li>
          <li><strong>Steep slope (&gt; 30°)</strong>: <strong>+4,000 – 8,000 DH</strong> for safety
          equipment and installation complexity (indicative 2026 bracket)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          A concrete terrace with easy access remains the least costly configuration. If your roof is
          steep or made of fragile materials, budget for this surcharge.
        </p>

        <h2>The battery question: useful, but not cost-neutral</h2>
        <p>
          A <strong>battery-less</strong> installation (grid-connected) remains the most common and
          most profitable solution for about 80% of urban homes. With Law 82-21 now in force (Decree
          2-25-100, June 2026), the surplus you don't self-consume can be injected into the grid — but
          only up to <strong>20% of your annual production</strong>, bought back at the ANRE tariff of
          <strong> 0.21 DH/kWh peak / 0.18 DH/kWh off-peak</strong> — well below what you pay to
          consume (0.90 – 1.66 DH/kWh depending on your ONEE bracket). Solar's value is therefore
          mainly in <strong>direct self-consumption</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>If you want to store energy for the evening or protect against outages, an LFP battery adds a significant cost:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>LFP battery 5 – 15 kWh: +22,000 – 60,000 MAD</strong> depending on capacity and brand (indicative 2026 bracket — sources: ecovolt.ma, electrosolarplus.ma)</li>
          <li>Payback stretches by <strong>1 to 3 years</strong> with a battery</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          For regular residential use without frequent-outage constraints, the grid plays the role of
          a free "virtual battery" — which explains why most Moroccan installations in 2026 remain
          without storage.
        </p>

        <h2>VAT and customs duties: an important nuance</h2>
        <p>Morocco's solar tax regime in 2026 is <strong>not uniform</strong>:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Bare photovoltaic panels</strong>: <strong>VAT-exempt</strong> — but with no
          input-VAT deduction right. For an individual, this is neutral. For a VAT-liable business,
          the lack of deductibility can reduce the benefit.</li>
          <li><strong>Turnkey installation</strong> (supply + installation): subject to
          <strong> 20% VAT</strong> — but with deduction rights for liable professionals. The price
          brackets in this guide are stated including VAT for individuals.</li>
          <li><strong>Inverters</strong>: customs duties on inverters have changed — they dropped
          from <strong>17.5% to 2.5%</strong> for imported models, which contributed to lowering
          their market cost in 2026 (source: lechantier.ma, fnh.ma).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If you're a business or investor, have your VAT situation checked by an accountant: the
          treatment can vary depending on the legal nature of the installation.
        </p>

        <h2>Return on investment: 5 to 7 years residential</h2>
        <p>
          The payback most often cited by Moroccan installers for a standard residential installation
          (without battery) is <strong>5 to 7 years</strong> — indicative 2026 bracket, consistent
          with several sources (solaropeak.com, ecovolt.ma, fnh.ma). With a battery, add
          <strong> 1 to 3 more years</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          This calculation depends heavily on your actual consumption and your ONEE tariff bracket. A
          household consuming more than 300 kWh/month (bracket at 1.45 DH/kWh, or beyond 500 kWh at
          1.66 DH/kWh) recovers its installation faster than a low consumer — solar is all the more
          profitable the higher your current bill is.
        </p>
        <p>
          For more on real savings by city and profitability simulations, see our article
          <a href={L('/blog/rentabilite-solaire-par-ville-maroc')}>Solar profitability by city in Morocco</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>How many panels do you need?</h2>
        <p>
          Before comparing prices, you need to know the right power for your household. A household
          consuming between 4,000 and 6,000 kWh/year generally needs <strong>3 to 5 kWc</strong>;
          between 6,000 and 10,000 kWh/year, more like <strong>5 to 8 kWc</strong>. Each kWc takes up
          about 5 to 6 m² of roof.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our dedicated guide explains the full method:
          <a href={L('/guides/combien-de-panneaux-pour-ma-maison')}>How many panels for my house?</a>
        </p>

        <h2>A last word before signing anything</h2>
        <p>
          Use these brackets to budget and to spot an offer that's abnormally low or abnormally
          expensive. But don't ask them for what they can't give: a firm price. Your roof
          configuration, your consumption, your ONEE bracket and the distance between the panels and
          the electrical panel move the final total, sometimes by several thousand dirhams.
        </p>
        <p>
          The only figure that counts for your house comes from reading your bill and a visit.
          That's exactly what our diagnostic does, free of charge and with no obligation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <RelatedLinks
        links={[
          { href: L('/blog'), label: 'All the articles' },
          { href: L('/guides'), label: 'The evergreen guides' },
          { href: L('/prix-panneaux-solaires-maroc'), label: 'Solar panel prices in Morocco (evergreen)' },
        ]}
      />
    </article>

    <CtaBand title="Market brackets only go so far. Your bill gives the exact number." href={L('/devis/mon-toit')} />

    <StickyCta />
  </div>
</Layout>
